column168: The carton was leaking due to container failure causing release of product. An associate was gathering information and sat in a spot that had been soaked by the product. The the associate had not realized that fact until he had a burning sensation from his posterior. He informed his supervisor who informed him to immediately strip from the contaminated clothing and wash the affected area. The associate was given a spare article of clothing and was taken to the ER for documentation and observation. The associate was released without any lasting ill effect from the material last night. The spill was completed by 2000, the associate returned from observation by 0100 and went home until next shift today. All product was absorbed with oil dry and placed into a salvage drum and was handled according to all local, state, and federal regulations.

On Sept2, 2008, at approximately 0800, company driver Robert Taylor was making a delivery at 8030 National HWY, Pennsauken, NJ.  He was delivering an order to a customer when he noticed the scent of Mineral Spirits coming from his trailer.  He noticed a crimped down three (3) inch bung located on top of the IBC had popped off.  It is believed the release occurred within ten (10) minutes of identification as the driver noticed nothing out of the ordinary at his previous stop.  A supervisor was summoned to the site with a replacement lid.  The remnant was cleaned up and a replacement lid installed correcting the problem.  An investigation of the incident determined that the crimped bung was not completely sealed, eventually leading to the failure.  New equipment was purchased to enable for verification of proper seal.  Training on the use of the equipment will be completed in October, 2008.
column169: New equipment was purchased to verify a proper seal on the three inch bung.  Training on this new equipment will occur in October, 2008.

At 05:18, on September 5, 2008, a car inspector at the CSXT Pensacola, FL railyard noticed a strong ammonia odor. The yardmaster placed a call to 911 to notify the local fire deptartment.  A CSXT response contractor, SWS, responded for air monitoring and to locate the leaking car. SWS personnel found tank car GAMX 9315, a loaded Anhydrous Ammonia car, leaking from the vapor valve due to it not being properly closed and the outlet plug being less than tool tight. The valve was closed and plug was tightened wrench tight. The leak was stopped, and the car was released for movement.     Cause Code: 380  NARRI:  5 (5+9+0) x (2+0) = 140

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On September 10, 2008 at 03:30, personnel in the CSXT Willard, OH yard discovered UTLX 950676, a loaded tank car of ammonia, anhydrous, leaking from its top area. The car was isolated and the Willard, OH Fire Department was notified. CSXT's Manager-Hazardous Materials responded to the scene. At 03:55 a CSXT Hazmat manager inspected UTLX 950676, and noted a vapor cloud, approximately 2 feet wide x 6 feet long, emanating from within the protective housing. Operations about the tank car were curtailed. CSXT dispatched Eagle Construction + Environmental Services, Inc. (ECESI), Findlay, OH. ECESI personnel, along with two CSXT Hazardous Materials managers, inspected UTLX 950676 (Seal "PCS 21010" was intact on the protective housing). They broke the seal to inspect the fittings and found the "B" end liquid line valve open 1/2 turn with its plug being less than tool tight, both of which were corrected at that time. This allowed liquid to leak from this fitting. They also noted a vapor leak at the "A" end liquid line valve at the interface of the liquid line valve operating stem and its packing gland nut. The packing gland nut could not be tightened. A "Midland" style capping kit was employed to contain the release. Shipper representatives arrived and inspected the car, and a decision was made to transfer the tank car contents. Product from UTLX 950676 was transferred into PLMX 135552 on 09/11/08. Mr. Casebolt advised he would obtain FRA Movement Approval for UTLX 950676 to be returned to their Lima, OH facility.   Cause Code: 317  NARRI: 5 (5+9+0) X (2+0) = 140

column168: On 09/08/2008 at 19:44, personnel in the CSXT Kayne Avenue yard reported NATX 300784, a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S., leaking from the top of the rail car when it was moved . The rail car was isolated and the shipper and local agencies were notified of the incident. SWS, an CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a defective manway gasket under the manway lid. SWS replaced the manway gasket and decontaminated the rail car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport to destination.              NARRI :  5 (5+3+0) * (2+0) = 80  Cause Code = 209 /  NAR POINTS = 5

A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 200908 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with a product slosh that emanated from the manway nozzle area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and GATX 200908 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 200908 and found the manway securement bolts/nuts tight. Further investigation into the manway securement revealed that the manway gasket was missing. The responder applied a new gasket and resecured the manway cover by 0800 PDT, 9/03/08. All spillage on the tank shell that didn't evaporate was wiped. No ground spillage was evident. Afterwards, no further product leakage was observed during subsequent rail movements of GATX 200908 in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: One Wrapped pallet of 24 cases of battery fluid acid was in the nose of the trailer.  Another pallet beside it in the trailer must have scraped against the pallet of hazmat when the pallet was loaded beside it.  The pallet tore the cardboard and pierced the inner plastic liner of one carton, causing   the battery fluid to leak out onto the trailer floor.  The carton contained 6 quarts total that was divided between 4 bags within that carton.  We can't tell how many of the plastic inner bags were leaking.  We put the carton inside a plastic lined salvage container.

column169: Take the extra couple minutes in all steps of handling to ensure the security of the freight and the safety of the handling parties.  A driver picking up should check for any leaks upon pickup of from the shipper to ensure ABF's liability in the taking over of the freight.  At all handling and break   points, be gentle with the freight, and be extra cautious with hazardous materials.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Driver loaded his sixth and final load for his shift, exited the plant and proceeded to his destination unaware that when he closed the vent valve it did not close. Failure of the brake interlock system located at the vent valve permitted the unit to move with the vent valve in the open position. The driver was notified by another driver as he was entering the delivery facility which was approximately 16 miles away that he had product leaking from his trailer. Upon checking, he realised he did have a leak coming from the vent valve and notified local dispatch. Local dispatch notified the safety department, (emergency responders). Local county sheriff contacted to respond to the varoius spills on the roadway to control traffic while cleanup was done. Various crews from CTL responded and neutralized spill with soda ash and completed cleanup. Cleanup time was approximately 5/6 hours.
column169: All drivers pulling this type equipment will be re-trained on an additional safety check when they complete the pre-trip inspections to verify the brake interlock system is operational.  Immediately put in action was all drivers were verbally notified of the failure and how to check unit prior to loading.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While at the Marathon Truckstop off Interstate 75 at Exit 29, a leak was discovered coming from the LandStar trailer.  Site was secured, pending contractor assistance.  Eco-Tech USA, LLC of London, Kentucky was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection of the trailer, one (1) 5-gallon bucket of printing ink was discovered punctured.  Approximately 4.5 gallons of free product were released to the trailer floor.  Approximately 1 teaspoon released to the gravel surface outside the trailer, prior to contractor arrival.  Eco-Tech USA, LLC proceeded to offload the trailer.  Corncob absorbent material was applied to the trailer floor to remove residual product.  The damaged bucket was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, along with the spent absorbents, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  Remaining freight was restacked, repalletized, secured, and sent on to its destination.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a forklift puncture during loading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  LandStar Ranger, Inc. and Seigwerk USA Company will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: September 12, 2008: Received phone call from FRA Cheif Inspector J. Moore, advising tank car UTLX 11233, load, Waste Corrosive Acidic, Organic, NOS, was noted leaking from the top near the fill hole, just after the local Conrail crew had interchanged the car to the DuPont, Chambers Works Plant, Deepwater, NJ inbound track at Carneys Point Yard.    Further inspection by DuPont personnel advised leak was originating from inbetween the car's fill hole cover and manway nozzle.  It was not determined, when later inspected by DuPont at the car's unloading spot location inside the Deepwater, NJ WWT, if the cause of the release was due to loose or misapplied fill hole cover securement nuts (4 total), misaligned fill hole cover, or another cause.        Car to be decontaminated and cleaned by DuPont, WWT Plant, Deepwater, NJ personnel.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: During a routine inspection (9/17/08) of the container/tanks of the Horizon Hawk, HK018W, it was discovered that the portable tank, IECU100015-0/CA2057663, was dispersing gas through one of four presure relief valves. This portable tank was loaded in Oakland on 9/10/08 and transited through Honolulu on 9/14/08 on it's way to Guam.  Shipper was contacted and he provided some direction of freeing-up the valve by pouring water over the valve. It was estimated that one gas gallon was dispersed, although due to the small relief valve orifice it is uncertain of the exact amount. The dispersement occurred for about 10 hours. The direction from shipper and possibly the change of the sun direction resulted in valve closing.
column169: It is recommended that the shipper as well as the supplier place special attention to amount of product and condition of the relief valves for these shipments. They should also take into consideration the temperature changes these tanks will transit through for the period in route.

column168: On September 10, 2008 at 07:40, personnel in the CSXT Riverdale, Illinois, Barr Yard, discovered PROX 29824, a residue tank car of Liquid Petroleum Gas, leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and shipper, local, and federal agencies as applicable were notified (CHEMTREC Report #, 2008-09-10-00042). Eagle Construction, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line to be 1/8 turn open, and plug out.  Eagle personnel also found the vapor line valve 1/8 turn open and plug out and the sampling line plug out.  The liquid line appeared to have auto refrigerated. The leak was secured, the car properly sealed and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.  Cause Code:  117  NARRI:  5 (4+5+0) X (2+0) = 90

column168: On September 14, 2008 at 15:00, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard discovered PROX 15369, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. Veolia Environmental Services, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line closure cap was less than tool tight and allowed product to escape from tank car. column168: Driver using truck pump 3" Roper two 20 foot sections of 2 inch hose from trailer outlet valve to pump suction and one 20 foot 2 inch discharge hose to the customers receiving inlet line. driver was given the okay to start pumping. seconds into the material transfer the discharge hosr parted from the coupling at the customers connection. our 2 inch hose parted fron its quick connect coupling. product spilled into a containment area and was coptured in a sump. driver and operator were slightly exposed to the materisl but were both wearing their PPE on injuries. Investigation shows that the plant keeps the storage tank inlet valve closed as they flush their line through a perging valve. The operator got more air than product so he closed the valve. Our driver had no knowledge of this and kept pumping.  When the operator closed the valve the pressure build up was too much and the end parted from the hose.
column169: The carrier is investigation two areas of concern. First,the cariers pump has an internal by-pass and if operating properly the hose may not have failed. Second, the hose was just over a year old and is rated for a working pressure of 200 PSI our pumps do not produce 200 PSI . Carrier has a hose testing policy and test documentation shows this hose passed its pressure and visual inspection.

column25: OOCL USA Inc. for Steebins Engineering + Manufacturing Co.
column168: During a random inspection by FRA and US Coast Guard inspectors at the BNSF intermodal facility, container OOLU 169786 was observed and reported leaking an unknown liquid substance in the intermodal parking lot. BNSF contract responders immediately responded to investigate, stop the liquid release and remediate all spillage. Visqueen poly sheeting was placed along side OOLU 169786 and this container was removed from the chassis it was riding upon and placed atop the sheeting. Inspection of the lading inside OOLU 169786 revealed no blocking and bracing applied to this shipment. The sources of the liquid leak were two 55 gallon steel drums (UN Specification 1A1/Y1.2/100/B/BLR/08/RL) of a resin solution. Both of the drums had the bottom drum heads distended with stress fractures in the bottom heads, allowing the resin to escape. The UN Specification indicated that both of these drums were reconditioned in 2008. The remaining lading inside OOLU 169786 was removed and staged to be loaded inside another suitable container, properly blocked and braced for oceanic export. Once emptied, the inside of OOLU 169786 was cleaned and outside spillage remediated. The two leaking drums were deheaded and placed into a roll-off bin along with impacted pallets and cleaning materials for appropriate waste disposal.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Deterioration or Aging
column168: A HydroChem drivers, driving a truck with a flat bed containing four (4) totes of hydrochloric acid picked up from Red Bird Supply in Orange, TX, hit a bump on I10W in Channelview, TX.  The driver immediately checked the load in his mirrors and saw that one of the 330-gallon totes was leaking.  He immediately exited the freeway at Monmouth Street in Channelview, TX.  Emergency response personnel were contacted immediately. A catch pan was placed under the tote to capture the spill.  Soda ash and absorbent was place on the spill on the roadway and curb.  Absorbent was placed around the stormwater drain to reduce quantity of acid runoff to the drain.  The remaining acid in the leaking tote was transfered to another tote.  Upon inspection, the leaking tote was old and discolored and had a 6" horizontal crack approximately 1' from the top of the tote.  There wer no identification numbers or inspection stickers found on the tote.  United States Environmental Services (USES) was contracted to clean up the spill which was accomplished that day.  Event duration 2.5 hours.  Spill duration approximately 2 hours.  Three (3) drums of spill/soda ash/absorbent will be disposed at a PSC facility in Houston, TX.
column169: Always inspect containers carefully prior to loading.  If there is any doubt to the condition of the container, refuse to load.  Order chemical from a reputable vendor that uses approved and inspected containers for the products they hold.  Avoid lanes of traffic where there are many bumps and potholes in the road to reduce damage to load.

Flange was properly aligned with bolts and nuts put in place and secured. Leak stopped and car was decontaminated then returned to transportation.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: THE IBC CONTAINERS HAVE A PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE WHICH ALLOWS THE CYCLOHEXANE TO VENT.  THE DEVICE FAILED AND RUPTURED DURING TRANSPORTATION CAUSING ABOUT 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL TO BE RELEASED ONTO THE TRUCK FLOOR.  NO MATERIAL LEAKED OUTSIDE THE VEHICLE. ALL MATRIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY TRAINED VEOLIA EMPLOYEES. ALL SPILL DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO APPROPRIATE CONTAINERS AND LABELED FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: The pressure relief valves (PRV) that were in the stainless steel IBCs were the correct pressure (3PSI) that the IBCs were tested for, but the material grade has plastic threads on the (threaded portion) and the relief "popper" part of the device is not as sturdy as the other type of PRV.  Veolia will be switching out any PRVs in these units to a new device which is much stronger and made of stainless steel. The new PRVs are also rated for 3 PSI.  Veolia employees have been instructed to replace any (old style PRV) with the new Stainless Steel PRVs before shipment. The older style PRVs were not defective just not made of the same quality that the stainless devices are.

column168: Our Owner Operator rolled his vehicle and the trailer while making a right hand turn.  The trailer's dome lid was crushed open during the rollover spilling 4700 gallons of hydrochloric acid.  The duration of the release is estimated to be about 15 minutes.      Fortunately, the accident occured in a very rural area of Texas with no waterways nearby.  The vehicle slid into a ditch that runs parallel to the road. The spillage was contained by the ditch.    The spill was cleaned up by a professional environmental service.
column169: This incident reinforced the importance of navigating any turn or curve slowly.  We immediately sent out a Safety Alert and additional safety training material.  Each branch of our company held a safety meeting to discuss this incident and proper driving techniques.    The rollover protection for the dome lid failed in this case.  Maybe the rollover protection for this particular trailer needs further investigating.  We have contacted the trailer manufacturer to provide them with details of the accident.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery to the Masonite Door Corporation, the Slay Transportation, Co., Inc. driver accidentally overfilled the storage tank.  Approximately 10 gallons of free product were released and impacted some concrete.  Masonite Door Corporation personnel applied absorbent material and absorbent pads to contain the free liquid on the impacted concrete surface.  Masonite Door Company will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: The material inside the drum is septic material that had sodium hypochlorite and lime added to the material to cut down the smell and the biological content would be rendered "dead". The drum pressurized and burst the removable lid from the drum. This all occured inside the Veolia service truck with no release to the environment. Veolia trained employees cleaned the material up and overpacked the drum for shipment. It was determined the drum built up pressure from the material inside and the pressure was very high and burst the lid off the container. No one was hurt in this incident.
column169: The other 13 drums in the shipment were vented to help relieve any build up of pressure, before the shipment was sent to the disposal location. There were no other problems with the shipment. Future shipments of this material will be vented to prevent any reoccurance. Veolia employees are being retrained on this"special project"

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery to Speedway Gas Station, the McKinley Trucking Co., Inc. driver accidentally overfilled the underground storage tank.  Approximately 15 gallons of free product were released and impacted some nearby storm drains.  Speedway Gas Station personnel applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  The Romulus Fire Department and the Romulus Police Department responded to assess the site.  Inland Waters of Detroit, Michigan was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Inland Waters proceeded to flush the contaminated storm drains and recovered the contaminated absorbent material.  Inland Waters will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, McKinley Trucking Co., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column14: EB Etiwanda on ramp to I-10
column168: Driver was dispatched to make route deliveries at about 1410 hrs. At about 1430 hrs. a phone call was received at Airgas West Cucamonga, CA from the California Highway Patrol office that our truck was overturned and on fire.  CHP advised that there was one fatality, the driver of the truck. Several managers responded and arrived at about 1500 hrs. Fire was extiguished. Cryogenics manager examined the pressure vessel. No release was observed.  The Carbon Dioxide was removed from the vessel.  The vessel was uprighted.  The I-10 was stopped in both directions for about 20 minutes.  Unit was towed to a secure storage facility.

column168: Entrained DGCX 1076 (DOT 112J340W tank car) that arrived earlier on an inbound train in the railyard was reported with frost on its top protective housing body. DGCX 1076 was carefully setout from the train and cordoned off in the railyard. Shipper responders reported finding the protective housing seal intact. Detailed inspection revealed the B-end liquid valve's closure plug was 4 turns less than tool tight and the valve was slightly open (less than 1/8 turn to close). All other valves and fittings were checked and found secure. Response was concluded by 1900 hrs. MDT, 9/24/08.

column168: A BNSF roadswitch crew working in the railyard reported exposure to a chemical odor emanating from an unknown source. The crew left the area and as a precaution were taken to a local hospital for medical evaluation and examination. A chemical screening test and oxygen were administered to four BNSF employees. The employees were released with no medical prescriptions provided and incurred no lost work days.  BNSF contract responders arrived and initiated air monitoring and rail car inspections. Several rail cars were inspected to determine the chemical odor source. Inspections revealed UTLX 200142 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) to be the odor source. The valve protective housing cover was found partially open (not closed completely) and the intact security seal (TBS 299691) was looped through the chain of the unapplied housing retaining pin. The liquid line had a 3 inch aluminum male cam-lock fitting still attached in the valve riser which prevented full closure of the housing cover. The liquid valve was in the closed position, but its closure plug was not applied due to the cam-lock fitting in place. Product residue was found on the outside of the valve and around the valve's base. A small amount of product was visible and surrounded the stainless steel ball in the ball valve body. The cam-lock fitting was removed with some difficulty as some of its threads were galled. Once removed, the product inside the valve body was absorbed and wiped with shop towels. Spillage on the valve body and valve base was also wiped. The liquid valve's 3 inch closure plug threads were re-taped with PTFE (Teflon) sealing tape. This plug was applied and tool tightened. Also, the vapor valve's one inch closure plug was found to be hand tight with no sealing tape on its threads. This closure plug was removed, threads taped, reinserted and tool tightened. The housing covered was then closed and properly pinned with SRS seal numbered 00330 applied. Afterwards, no product odor from UTLX 200142 was detectable and response was concluded at 1430 hrs. CDT, 9/28/08.

NATX 300409 was noted by Norfolk Southern's contractor RSI Logistics personnel after removing the bottom outlet valve cap and prior to commencing unloading with product leaking from the bottom outlet.      The leak was stopped by reinstalling and tighteneing the bottom outlet valve cap.  The valve operating handle was noted as having excessive play when closed.  The valve handle was partially closed and secured in place which stopped the release.  The car was unloaded without further incident.        The car was bad ordered to a tank car shop for further inspection and repairs to the defective bottom outlet valve.  Car moved under FRA Movement Approval FRA-08090325.    All material that leaked from the car was contained and properly disposed of.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: GATX 14545 was noted by carrier personnel with product dripping from the bottom outlet valve.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Sunpro, responded and properly closed the top operated bottom outlet valve operating handle and cap stopping the release.  There was also a release due to defective packing around the TOBOV operating handle stem.  The defective packing was replaced stopping the release.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: ADMX 30399 was noted by Norfolk Southern contractor RSI Logistics persoonel with product between the bottom outlet valve and cap prior to beginning unloading.  The cap was reinstalled stopping the release.    Subsequent attempts to remove the cap resulted in the same leakage being noted from the bottom outlet valve.  The car was unloaded without incident and will be sent to a tank car shop under FRA Movement Approval for further inspection and repairs.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: A van trailer picked up a load of drums at the shipper's location and was transported to the carrier's ten day in-transit storage facility.  Upon arrival, when the rear door was opened, facility personnel noticed a small amount of material had leaked onto the floor of the trailer.  Facility personnel activated the facility's emergency response team who donned the appropriate PPE, entered the trailer, and determined which drum was leaking.  A small dent near the bottom of the chime of the drum had caused the small pinhole leak.  The drum was placed into a suitable salvage drum along with all absorbent materials used in the clean up.  The salvage drum and the others in the shipment were then loaded into another van trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The driver was re-instructed to use proper caution in inspecting drums prior to acceptance for shipment.  Review of drum packaging and inspection was also recommended to the shipper.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler came across a drum in the nose of the trailer that had leaked some of its contents from the large bung closure on the lid of the drum. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and loose bung closure was tightened to prevent further unintentional release. Drum was forwarded to ultimate consignee without further incident. No action contributed to this failure other than a loose bung closure.

column63: PACKAGE IN OVERPACK CONTAINER, UNABLE TO
column168: Hazardous material was loaded on top of a pallet and not blocked properly to the front. During transit, 1 box fell btween 2 pallets, at time of unloading, the box was pushed causing a spill of 2 quarts from the inner bag. Using plastic gloves, the box was turned to its side to stop and contain the chemical, the box was then placed in a spill recovery drum. The product was allowed to evaporate and quickly disapated as the release was contained in the trailer. The duration of the release was aproximately 5 seconds.
column169: The loader of this shipment should have used better judgement in the location loaded, also more should have been done to block and brace the hazardous material freight.

column168: Leon Hendrickson, Manager of Hazardous Materials reported a estimated release of one gallon of phosphoric acid from the vacuum relief valve from Tankcar UTLX 12003 in the Montpelier Yard in Montpelier, ID. The tank car was isolated, a new vacuum relief valve was installed.  UTLX 12003 was decontaminated, inspected and released to transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: GATX 37321 was found by UPRR Mechanical Department personnel to be releasing product from the top of the tank car.  Lane Sekavec, Manager Hazardous Materials responded and found the manway partially unsecured.  One manway swing bolt was in the down position and two swing bolts were not hand tight.  The gasket was checked and the found to be in good condition.  Mr. Sekavec re-secured the manway cover and, after being cleaned, the the car was released to continue in transportation.  Approximately twenty gallons of product were released in two locations in Neff Yard.  SUPPLEMENTAL REMARKS: GATX 37321 WAS FOUND TO BE RELEASING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR. INSPECTION OF THE CAR FOUND THE CAR MANWAY PARTIALLY UNSECURED, ONE MANWAY SWING BOLT WAS IN THE DOWN POSITION AND TWO SWING BOLTS WERE NOT TIGHT. THE MANWAY COVER WAS SECURED, THE CAR CLEANED, AND RELEASED.
column169: Insure shippers properly secure tank car closures.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: GATX 60926, load of hydrochloric acid, was reported to be releasing product from the top of the tank car.  Inspection by Hydro-Klean (Contractor) revealed the frangible disk had ruptured, allowing a minimal amount of product to be released to the top of the car.  ERCO Worldwide (Shipper) responded and installed a replacement frangible disk.  Hydro-Klean had previously decontaminated the top of the tank car and it was released to continue in transportation.
column169: Shipper should inspect the frangible disk prior to each move to ensure that the disk is in proper condition for containing the product during transportation.

column168: Under file number 23286, Quality Carriers reported a overturned tractor-tanker incident.  There was no release of product from the trailer, but the product would need to be transfered to a new trailer before the overturned trailer could be uprighted.  The US Ecology response team was the first team on site and secured the site.  Once the new trailer arrived, US Ecology personnel completed the transfer.

When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a box that had slightly leaked some of its contents. Further investigation revealed that when the freight was originally loaded the forklift operator that staged it in the trailer must have unknowingly punctured the box with the forkblade when loading it. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged box.

column168: On September 13, 2008 at 00:45, personnel in the CSXT AACA Yard discovered GATX 200899 a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S., with a slosh leak from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Verasun Marketing (C/O US BIO Platte Valley) and VA EOC were notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a broken self reclosing PRD. column168: On September 15, 2008 at 15:07 personnel in the CSXT Flint, Mi yard were advised by Mr. Scott Hoose, FRA, Hazmat Inspector, that GATX 14360, a tank car, residue last contained liquefied petroleum gas, was observed leaking vapor. CSXT dispatched a CSXT response contractor, Young's Environmental Company, Inc. (YECI). YECI personnel found vapor leaks at the gauging device due to its packing gland nut not being suffficiently tight, and at the "B" end liquid line valve and its closure plug. YECI personnel made six full turns to the packing gland nut to stop the vapor release at the gauging device, and advised that, although the "B" end liquid line valve was fully closed and its plug tool tight, vapor passed between the two. The leak was stopped by removing the valve plug, wrapping it in teflon tape and tool tightening it into the valve. CSXT advised shipper personnel (Mr. Jeff Angle) that they must obtain FRA Movement Approval for GATX 14360 to continue in transportation or make repairs in accord with all U. S. DOT Regulations.   Cause Code: 509  NARRI: 5 (4+5+0) X (2+0) = 90
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On September 17th at 12:00 in CSXT's Hamlet Yard, FRA Inspector Roger Huff discovered GPPX9297, a loaded tank car of Resin Solution, leaking product from top of car.  The car was isolated and Chemtrec (report number 2008092300093) assisted in contacting the shipper, Georgia Pacific LLC.  Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to  the scene and found the cause of the release was due to two of eight manway cover securement blots / nuts being less than tool tight.  Hepaco representatives checked the condition of the manway gasket then properly tightened the securement bolts / nuts with a wrench.  The railcar was then decontaminated and released to destination.  Approximately one gallon was released from the container.  As an additional note: although properly secured evidence of fresh product was noted near the air inlet / vapor line valve.  This fitting should be inspected by a qualified repair facility to ensure integrity.   Cause Code:  200  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: Ensure to utilize a procedure checklist form in an effort to ensure each container is properly secured for transportation.

column168: On September 17, 2008 at 16:54, personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered ADMX 30530, a loaded tank car of Alcohol N.O.S., leaking from liquid line. The car was isolated and shipper, local, and yard personnel were notified (CHEMTREC Report # 2008-09-17-00198). A CSXT hazardous materials manager and Car General Foreman responded and found the valve stem on the liquid line was loose and the packing nut was tightened.  The product leaked from this area and caused a small release to the top of the car.  There was no release to the ground. After repair, the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move to place the car in a protective area.  Cause Code: 296  NARRI: 2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32

column168: On 09/26/08 at 08:20, personnel in the CSXT Russell, KY yard discovered PPGX1574, a residue tank car of Chlorine, leaking from the top protective housing area of the rail car.  The car was isolated and the area of the yard was vacated.  The shipper, BRENNTAG Mid South and Consignee, PPG Industries, were notified of the incident, and local, State and Federal notifications were made.  A CSXT contractor was dispatched to the scene.  The CSXT contractor was placed in a backup role by local public agency incident command, and a response team from Marathon (Greenup, KY) made entry to the car and stopped the leak by turning all four valves at least one turn each.  Marathon reported that the plugs were tight.    A CSXT seal was placed on the protective housing, and the car was held for PPG Industries to inspect before leaving for destination.   Cause Code: 117  NARRI:  5 (4+10+0) x (2+0) = 140

A driver arrived at a loading facility to load an oil and water mixture into a 1100 gallon compartment of a 2 compartment non code cargo tank motor vehicle.  During the loading operation, the driver miscalculated the amount of volume he had remaining in the tank and overfiled the compartment allowing approximately 20 gallons of oil and water escape from the top manway onto the asphalt parking area. The driver immedialtey stopped the loading operation and utilized available containment equipment to contain the release.  Facility personnel were notified and a suitable absorbant material was used to absorb the free liquid.  In addition, an emergncy response crew was dispatched to the scene and all spill debris was collected and placed in suitable containers.  the side of the cargo tank was cleaned and all debris used in this cleaning operation were containerized for diosposal.  ALl material collected as a result of this incident were sent for disposal to a fully licensed waste management facility.
column169: IN order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been counseled on his responsibility when loading a cargo tank.  Of particular concern is the requirement that the driver ensure that he has visibility to the volume remaining in the tank during loading and to ensure sufficient outage is left in the tank to revent an overfill and/or unintentional release.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Covered hopper car CEFX 75076 was on jacks to be re-wheeled by carrier personnel when the car fell off the jacks causing minor damage to the pneumatic unloading tube.  The damage consisted of a crack at the tube cap which closed when the car was picked up and the pressure was removed from the tube. The crack was sealed and taped to prevent product loss.  The car was forwarded to destination without further incident.  After unloading the car will be shopped for further inspection and permanent repairs.  About 8 ounces of product was recovered and properly disposed of.

column168: Driver was transferring product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  The driver didn't have a means to accurately measure the amount in the storage tank and it overflowed about 1 gallon.  Spill went into a containment area
column169: The storage tank was supposedly see-through to determine the level but it was dark and cloudy out.  The tank was grey in color and the driver could not determine the level. Driver should have refused to make the delivery unless level could be verified.  Driver suggested the tank should have a sight glass on it.

column168: When driver got to the shipper to load the cargo tank, she was informed that she would have to use the pump on her tractor to load the cargo tank from the bottom.  After about an hour, she wanted to stop the pump and go up on top of cargo tank to check the level and the plant personnel said it was too early, it wouldn't be full yet.  A few minutes later it overflowed.  The plant hosed the spill to their containment system.
column169: Driver should not have relied on the advice of anyone else.  The plant should also have had a way to measure the amount going into the trailer and stop it at a certain point.

WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A 55 GALLON DRUMS OF LIQUID WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE SEAL, AND SEAM, LOCATED AROUND THE LID AND RIM OF THE DRUM.  THE LID ON THE DRUMS WAS TIGHTENED, AND NO FURTHER LIQUID SEAPED OUT.  THE AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS. column169: BETTER SECUREMENT OF CAP OR LIDS ON DRUMS.  DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF PAILS, DRUMS, TOTES OR MISCELLANEOUS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING.  THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT.  THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWERS TO PREVENT PACKAGING DETERIORATION.  IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE.  TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED.  DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHTLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: At 10:00 AM, on 9/21/2008, tank car UTLX 204827, a load of Alcohols, N.O.S. (Ethanol), was found leaking from the manway area of the car while the car was being switched in the CSXT yard at Tampa, FL.  The car was isolated. The local Trainmaster inspected the car and found three manway cover bolts less than tool tight.  The manway bolts were secured wrench tight, the leak stopped and the car was released for transportation. No clean up was required due to evaporation of the liquid. No special switching move was required.     Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (3+0) =  120

column168: A driver loaded this 55-gal plastic drum onto a trailer and failed to place protective plywood completely around it. He Nthen loaded a skid behind the drum with a forklift and pushed the skid against the drum, creating a small 1/2"puncture in the base of the drum. Approximately 35 gallons of product leaked out of the drum onto the trailer floorand onto the concrete yard of our facility. We called a local haz mat cleanup vendor and they were on site about 1hour later. They placed floor dry on the spill and contained the drum and the used floor dry into overpack drums.
column169: We are providing retraining to our driver who caused this spill, where he will learn the importance of placing drums on cardboard sheets and protecting them on all sides with sheets of plywood. The driver will also be disciplined percompany policy.

ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. column17: Environmental Housing, Inc,  DBA Sunshine Propane
column25: Environmental Housing, Inc.  DBA Sunshine Propane
column168: The vehicle was heading north on West Valley Road, a two-lane, paved secondary road, carrying about 1400 gallons of propane.  The truck left the road on the east (right) side of the road and slid approximately fifteen feet down a steep embankment and came to rest on its side.  The driver suffered a fractured rib and was airlifted to a hospital as a precautionary measure. He was released the same day.    On the truck, the meter head was broken off, and approximately ten gallons of propane vapor was released from the associated piping.  The duration of the release was approximately ten to fifteen minutes.  All of the automatic safety valves shut down, and there were no other leaks or spills.  The tank was not damaged.    The fire department sprayed water on the truck to disperse the propane leak.  Sunshine Propane employees shut off all of the manual valves and disconnected the truck battery.  They transferred the propane in the truck tank to an empty propane tanker.  The tow company righted the truck and towed it to its yard for the State Department of Transportation inspection.  The road was closed for approximately four hours.
column198: Environmental Housing, Inc. DBA Sunshine Propane

Orientation of the container is questionable because the freight had been moved about and was not in the original position.  Upon further inspection, it was found the innner metal drums were not sealed to HMR requirements (all inner seals were removed) allowing contents to spill easily.  The containers that were soaked (kerosene) were allowed to air out and were disposed of properly.
column169: Being as it was a combination package, we had no idea of the inner package condition until it leaked.  I did have a discussion with the offerer from BRW though and went over with her what to look for in a properly sealed container.  If a container looks like the one that spilled to never accept in the future.  We went over the proper seals and condition of the inner packagings as well as the reasons why this one failed.

column168: The station handling the spill advised that there were other packages with the shipment and at destination the recipient noticed this one box was damp so they refused it. After bringing it back to the station the specialist opened it to find two 1 Liter (approx.) paint cans inside with one of the lids loose. Neither lid was secured by any type of positive closure. The station was informed by the shipper that the paint was latex. Upon receiving the MSDS from the customer it indicated that it was flammable with a flashpoint of 104 F. The MSDS also indicated in section 14 Transport Details that it was UN1263, Paint, PGIII. John Barrett of the FAA was notified and the package is being held pending their investigation.

column168: On September 25th at 11:41, personnel in the CSXT Savannah Southover Yard discovered PPNX1230, a residue tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous Liquefied, releasing an odor.  The car was isolated and Chemtrec (report number 2008092500111) assisted in contacting the shipper, Hexion Specialty Chemicals.  SWS First Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the air inlet / vapor valve closure plug missing and the valve open one quarter turn.  SWS representatives closed the valve and secured the closure plug with a wrench.  The railcar was then decontaminated and released to destination.  Approximately 1 gallon was released from the container.  As additional information: original seal number 24504 was removed from the pressure housing cover and a new seal was applied prior to being released for transit. This incident did not require a special switching move.     Cause Code:  390  NARRI: 5 (4+9+0) x (2+0) = 130.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The shipment had other freight stacked on top causing the tops of the bottles to leak. The release was minimal per container. The boxes were overpacked and waiting disposition fro the shipper. The released product evaporated.

The "C" ring inside the hose quick connect / dry release assembly failed.  This caused the plunger to fall back loosely and allow the product inside the hose to flow freely.  The event lasted about 3-4 seconds. column168: GSL Pro# 533773 - Container Number TOLU 341441-2  This container was rejected by the BNSF railroad because it didn’t have any blocking and bracing. BNSF requires 1/2” plywood between the tiers of drums. We were unloading the drums in order to install the 1/2” plywood when we discovered spilled product on the floor of the container. The shipper had installed very thin plywood, but not between the tiers on the front row of drums. The pressure of the top drum compressed the lower drum and caused the product to ooze through the air hole in the drum plug.  We contained the small spill with Oil Absorb and placed it and the drum in a 95 gal over-pack drum.
column169: We asked the consignee to tell the shipper to use 1/2” plywood and place it between all of the upper and lower drums on all future shipments.

column169: DON'T LOAD A HEAVY SKID ON TOP OF A SKID OF HAZARDOUS PAILS. PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: Shipment was damaged by two different incidents by two different people on the same night. The first incident was byDSR J. Gentilly, who was moving the shipment down the dock on top of a pallet of freight from another shipment.Upon crossing an expansion joint in the dock one carton of the damaged shipment (pro 722-009971) fell on the dock,causing the lids of the pails to be bent and come loose, allowing the product to be released. DSR J. Gentillyproceeded to put speedy dry on spill and clean up, placing damaged carton and pails into a recovery drum with plastic liner, which was subsequently placed in the OS&D area of the dock. Release was limited to approximately10-15 minutes, allowing maybe 1 gallon of product to be spilled. This incident happened at 0115 on 09/29/2008.The second carton of shipment 722-009971 was damaged at approximately 0400 by DSR A. Rocha who was loading another shipment onto a P/D route trailer. A. Rocha placed the carton (722-009971) on top of the pallet he was loading, when he backed out of the trailer the carton fell causing the lids of the pails to be bent and come loose allowing the product to be released. DSR A. Rocha proceeded to put speedy dry on the spill, put the damaged carton and pails into the same recovery drum, and clean up the speedy dry. Release was approximately 1/2 gallon within about a 10 minute time frame.Pictures were taken and uploaded to the Con-way website.

column168: ON SEPT. 25 I RECEIVED A CALL FROM TIM CURTAIN ABOUT SOME CAUSTC SODA THAT WAS VISABLE ON TNEIR DRIVEWAY. HE EXPLAIN TO ME THAT DURING A DELIVERY OF 50% ON THE 25TH OF SEPT. SOME DILUTED CAUSTIC EXCAPED FROM AN OFF-LOADING HOSE AS THE TANKER DEPARTED. CONTENTS LOST WAS APPROX. 5-10 GALS.TIM EXPLAINED TO ME THAT THE DRIVE HAS A SHARP DECLINE WHICH ALLOWED THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM ANY HOSE THAT WAS NOT PROPER CAPPED. THE LINES WERE RINSED PRIOR TO DEPARTURE BUT WERE NIT CAPPED CORRECTLY. I HAVE SPOKEN TO TIM OF CANANDAFOVA SEVERAL TIMES SINCE THE INCIDENT. HE HAS STATED THAT THE SOLUTION WAS CLEANED BY HIS CREW ON THE DAY OF ONE INCIDENT AND ANYTHING LEFT BEHIND WAS WASHED AWAY BY A RAIN STORM.  NO VISIBLE CAUSTIC REMAINS. THE CASE IS CONSIDERED CLOSE AS TIM AND I ARE IN AGREEMENT.  THE PROD. WAS SOLVED ADEQUATELY.
column169: A COURSE OF ACTION HAS BEEN TAKEN IN THIS MATTRR. I HAVE SPOKEN WITH GEORGE AND HE IS AWARE OF THE PROPER PROCEDURE DURING LOADING/UNLOADING OF TANKERS.  HE STATED HE DIDN'T RECALL HAVING THE CAP OFF BUT WILL BE MUCH MORE DILIGENT IN OPERATIONS FROM HERE FORWARD.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-INSTRUMENTS OR ARTICLES
column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: Event occurrencce: 09/19/08,1100 hrs. Location: American Electric Power, Materials Facility, Bridgrnan MI. 49106:  Description of Events provided by ThermoFisher:  Normally all shipments of this product are shipped direct from our facility in Germany to our customers. As a result, the Oakwood Village, OH facility has not been a point of distribution for this product.  The DAI-6CC units were returned to the Thermo Fisher Scientific Oakwood Village, Ohio facility as a new product retum from a customer. The individual units were returned, packaged in unmarked fiberboard boxes. This is being addressed separately with this customer as a preventative action.  American Electric Power requested that the sources be removed from the product and sent to a separate address. Our customer service personnel generated a separate order for the shipment  the radioactive sources once they were removed from the DA1-6CC units. Reference customer order CO 130017.  The DA1-6CC units were pulled from stock and sent to the shipping department. Shipping personnel followed the notation on the order which indicated that the sources should be removed. The shipping personnel made the assumption that the sources were removed since there was no indication of the product being radioactive on the packaging as described above. Items were then mistakenly packaged and shipped as non haz-mat material.  Description of Events provided by American Electric Power:  On 09/19/08, the (2) area monitors were delivered to the AEP Materials Management Facility. The package was inspected and due to the waybill, the package was not inspected for radioactive material since the bill of lading stated that the sources were to be shipped separately to the DC Cook nuclear plant. The packages were then transported to the DC Cook nuclear plant where they were received onsite and custody transferred to the Radiation Protection Department (organization that ordered the items). When the packages were opened for inspection, the area monitors were to contain Sr-90 check sources (2 total). The Radiation Protection Department immediately quarrentined the area monitors, removed the Iwo check sources, then returned the area monitors to the materials management department for storage until the issue is resolved. Both check sources that were removed and placed in a secured radioactive material storage area.  A condition report was immediately generated and routed through the Environmental Department for review.
column169: Corrective Actions Initiated by ThermoFisher:All packaging has been labeled as radioactive.Change relevant part descriptions to include the word "radioactive".Improve current work instructions to reflect a verification process for radioactive shipments.Provide additional training of all personnel involved in radioactive shipments.Work order will be submitted to investigate and implement an enhancement to the MRP system to flag or notify shipping personnel of radioactive items and shipments.Corrective Actions Initiated by American Electric Power:AEP Material Management Department has placed a hold on all ThermoFisher outstanding purchase orders.Determine actions necessary to ensure we receive radioactive shipments from ThermoFisher that are properly packaged, marked, and labeled (assignment due 45 days).

column168: Driver fell asleep and ran off the road striking a guardrail.  The trailer transporting Carbon Dioxide, Refrigerated Liquid separated from the tractor and rolled down an embankment.  The trailer struck a parked car and the corner of a business.  Occupants were asked to leave from the houses either side of the damaged building.  The trailer subframe (suspension) was torn from the trailer and as a result the piping adjacent to the subframe was damaged and a leak occured.  Much of the insulationn of the cargo tank was torn off during the accident and the trailer was building pressure, but venting properly as desgned to maintain pressuresat acceptable levels.   The trailer had a slow release of CO2 for approximately 4 hours when it was decided that to upright the damaged tank, it would be best that all product be vented from the trailer.  It was not possible to attempt a transfer of the product due to the severity of damage.  The trailer was blown down to atmosphere and uprighted, then removed from the scene.     The driver sustained a lunbar strain and broken nose and was treated and released form the local hospital.
column169: Linde has implemented a fatigue awareness traiing program to address the impact of fatigue when driving.  We are also in the process of evaluating our dispatch sysem to address drivers returning to work after extended holidays (three day or longer weekends) and moving start times back for those drivers retuning with start times of midnight to 4am to allow additional opportunity for rest and adjusting back to the work schedule.    Improvements to the container are not indicated as this was a severe impact and the container actually held up very well considering the events.

column168: On Friday September 26, 2008 at approximately 6:45 PM EDT, Savage’s Philadelphia Ops Manager - Paul Chatburn was in his personal vehicle on the verge of departing from the TRANSFLO - Philadelphia (West), PA terminal.  Mr. Chatburn was pulling up to the main entrance/exit gate accessing Moore Street, when he heard a loud pop and viewed a subsequent vapor cloud on transfer track # 1, engulfing the spotted Acrylamide tank cars residing on the aforementioned track.  Mr. Chatburn, immediately returned to the office to obtain the product specific MSDS, activate the terminal’s emergency response plan and check on Ops Supervisor - James Houser who was closing up the silo transfer area.      At Approximately 6:48 PM, Mr. Chatburn radioed Ops Supervisor Mr. James Houser who was at the Soda Ash Silo System, notifying him of a vapor cloud originating from  Flocryl Acrylamide tank car GATX 70680 staged on track #1.  Mr. Chatburn instructed Mr. Houser to be mindful of the wind direction when attempting to return to the office in order to assist with internal company, external incident notifications.  Mr. Chatburn then proceeded to contact, 911 to report that a hazardous material incident (e.g., Acrylamide vapor release) was transpiring at the TRANSFLO - Philadelphia facility located at South 36th & Moore Streets in Philadelphia, PA (Grays Ferry) and he requires their assistance.      At approximately 6:50 PM, Mr. Chatburn contacted Savage’s General Manager - Randy Gifford to inform him that a hazardous material incident was presently occurring with vapor discharging from an Acrylamide tank car at the TRANSFLO - Philadelphia, PA terminal; Mr. Chatburn indicated to Mr. Gifford that he was about to leave from the facility when he heard a loud pop and a cloud formed on track # 1 engulfing the spotted Acrylamide tank cars.  Mr. Gifford encouraged Mr. Chatburn to contact Chemtrec and activate the terminal’s emergency response plan, and contact the shipper if he had not already done so at the present time.  Mr. Gifford made proceeding notification phone calls to TRANSFLO’s Manager of Field Operations - Marc Scena (left voice message on his cell) and conversed with Savage’s Director of SH&E - Rich Stanley describing the hazmat incident scenario transpiring at the TRANSFLO - Philadelphia, PA location.  Mr. Stanley proceeded to notify TRANSFLO’s Director of HSE&Q - Ms. Jan Barnes of the aforementioned event; Mr. Stanley indicated that he was in the Philadelphia area and could be on the scene in roughly an hour.      Mr. Chatburn then proceeded to contact Chemtrec to provide a verbal report of the hazardous material vapor release originating from Flocryl Acrylamide tank car GATX 70680 and solicit their advice and assistance; the following Chemtrec report number was assigned, Chemtrec report # 2008092600177.  Chemtrec also forwarded Mr. Chatburn onto Flocryl’s John Hennesy; Mr. Chatburn then described the above incident scenario to Mr. Hennesy and informed him that he was
column169: Corrective Action(s)  ¿ Unable to be determined at this point in time as the entities (Savage; TRANSFLO; CSX; Flocryl) do not know the apparent cause of the product polymerizing inside tank car GATX 70680.  This may not be able to be ascertained until the tank car returns to Flocryl’s plant in Riceboro, Georgia.  Flocryl’s Mgt has the intentions of cutting open the tank car’s shell upon its return to view any abnormalities (e.g., contaminates).

column168: ON SEPT. 16, 2008 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:15 AM UNIT #9, A TRANSPORT TRAILER AND TRUCK OWNED BY A & M OIL CO., L.L.C. ROLLED OVER WHILE MAKING THE TURN FROM 35 ST. ONTO GREENSBORO AVE. IN TUSCALOOSA, AL.  THE TRANSPORT WAS DELIVERING FUEL TO A LOCAL SERVICE STATION LOCATED JUST ONE BLOCK FROM THE ACCIDENT.  THE TANKER WAS CARRYING 8483 GALLONS OF UNLEADED REGULAR GASOLINE.  THE TANKER AND TRUCK ROLLED OVER AND LANDED ON IT'S TOP IN A GRASS AREA ADJACENT TO GREENSBORO AVE.  NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT.  THE CAB OF THE TRUNCK WAS CRUSHED AND THE DRIVER PRONOUNCED DEAD AT THE SCENE.  THE TANKER WAS DAMAGED IN THE REAR COMPARTMENT AND LEAKING FUEL.  THE TUSCALOOSA FIRE DEPT. AND POLICE BLOCKED OFF THE AREA AND TEMPORARILY WEDGED A PIECE OF WOOD IN THE SMALL CRACK TO MINIMIZE THE SPILLAGE.  THEY ALSO REINFORCED ALL DOME LIDS TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  A & M OIL CO. NOTIFIED SWS FIRST RESPONSE TEAM AND SENT ANOTHER TANKER TRUCK TO THE SCENE TO BEGIN REMOVING THE FUEL FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER.  THE FIRST RESPONSE TEAM BEGAN CLEAN UP WORK IMMEDIATELY UPON ENTERING THE SCENE.  THE FIRST RESPONSE TEAM ASSISTED A & M OIL CO. TRANSFERING THE REMAINING FUEL FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER INTO THE NEW TRUCK.  THE TRANSFER PROCESS TOOK APPROXIMATELY 4 - 5 HOURS.  THE DAMAGED TANKER AND TRUCK WERE UPRIGHTED AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.  THE ROADS WERE REOPENED WHILE THE FIRST RESPONDERS CONTINUED THEIR CLEAN UP PROCESS.  A & M OIL CO. TRANSFERED 7828 GALLONS, THE FIRST RESPONSE TEAM RECOVERED 458 GALLONS, 197 WAS UNACCOUNTED FOR.
column169: It appears from the police report and eye witness accounts that the driver was trying to make the turn too fast.  Additional training to raise awareness of potential rollover.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED JUST 3 MILES FROM THE DESTINATION SNOWFLAKE, AZ.  MR. COREA WAS DRIVING UP A SLIGHT UPGRADE TRAVELING AT 47 MPH. HWY 277 HAD JUST BEEN REPAVED WITH FRESH ASPHALT AND THERE WERE NO ROAD LINES OR MARKINGS.  WE DON'T KNOW HOW OR WHY HE WAS DISTRACTED BUT HE DROVE TO CLODE TO THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT AND IT GAVE OUT UNDER THE WEIGHT OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER.  THE RIGHT STEER TIRE, DRIVE TIRES AND TRAILER TIRES WENT OFF THE ROADWAY.  THE TIRES DROPPED OFF 12" TO 18" TO THE SHOULDER.  MR. COREA TRIED TO STEER THE TRUCK BACK UP ON THE ROAD BUT THE TRACTOR JACKKNIFED AND THE TRAILER STARTED SLIDING OUT INTO THE DAMP GRASS LAND.  AS THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER LINED UP IT STARTED ROLLING.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER ENDED UP ON ITS LEFT SIDE AND THE OUTER SKIN OF THE TRAILER SUSTAINED TWO CRACKS APROX 6" TO 8" LONG.  THE TRAILER WAS LAYING ON THE CRACKS AND THE GASOLINE WAS SEEPING OUT INTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY.  THE POLICE, FIRE, AND HAZMAT CREWS WERE DISPATCHED TO HELP IN THE RECOVERY OF PRODUCT.  A PUMP TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED TO THE AREA.  IT TOOK APROX. 10 HRS TO START PUMPIMG OUT THE TRAILER BEFORE THE TRAILER COULD BE RIGHTED.  3,419 GAL. OF GASOLINE SEEPED INTO THE GROUND.
column169: I FEEL THAT IF THE ROAD HAD BEEN FINISHED THE SHOULDER WOULD HAVE BEEN THE SAME HEIGHT AS THE ROADWAY AND THE TRUCK MIGHT HAVE BEEN ABLE TO STEER BACK ONTO THE ROAD.  I WOULD CONTINUALLY ENCOURAGE DRIVERS TO STAY FOCUSED ON DRIVING ACVTIVITIES.  BE EXTRA ALERT WHEN ENCOUNTERING UNUASAL ROAD CONDITIONS.

column168: The common camer driver (not an EMCO/company employee) took it upon himself to replace a gasket a the rear of the tanker and inside the external valve as that valve showed signs of leaking. After finishing the gasket installation, evidently the gasket was not properly/correctly seated, so the valve didn’t sit flush. The driver first opened the internal/safety valve, and then when the driver opened the external valve, product began to spray out in various directions at once, causing the chemical to contact the driver from head-to-foot. The chemical on the ground caused the driver to slip and fall, hitting his head on the ground. The driver got up and first closed the external vilve and then closed the internal/safety valve. An EMCO employee who saw what had happened escorted the driver to an on-site shower facility, where he removed his clothes and took a thorough shower. He was provided with disposable garments by EMCO. Once it was discovered the employee had gotten chemical on himself, the North Chicago EMS was called and responded to the incident and after evaluating the driver, took him to the local hospital, along with a copy of the spilled chemical’s MSDS.  All of the released material was contained on-site, above ground, inside a diked area. EMCO’s on-site HazMat Team was deployed to thoroughly remove/clean up the spill, along with removing chemical from the rear of the tanker, which was also inside the diked containment area. Absorbent pads were first used to absorb the spilled material and then the area and vehicle was wiped down with an isopropanol/ammonia/water solution as specified on tie MSDS.  Once the driver was released from the hospital, he returned to EMCO and checked his vehicle prior to leaving the facility.
column169: The common carrier driver should have informed someone at IMCO that he was attempting to fix/replace the external valve gasket. We had no idea the driver was doing this; he was doing it without our knowledge cc permission. If he had informed someone at EMCO, we would have had one of our maintenance employees make the repair and/or assist the driver when replacing the gasket and then test the gasket replacement under controlled conditions to make sure product was not released on any individual or the ground. Ideally, the repair should have been performed while the tanker was empty.  in addition, the same driver had been at our facility approximately two weeks earlier with the same tanker and the driver was notified at that time the external valve had a very minor leak (we placed a bucket under the valve at that time to collect any material that dripped out) and that it should be repaired before the tanker returns to our facility.  The carrier was notified about the incident and the driver was informed he cannot make any repairs to his vehicle (tractor, tanker, etc.) without our expressed permission first and proper supervision during the repair by ore of our qualified employees.

column168: THIS LETTER IS TO PROVIDE AN OVER VIEW OF THE RECENT INCIDENT THAT TOOK PLACE AT 7:59AM ON THE 27TH DAY OF SEPTEMBER 2008.  TALEN'S EMPLOYEE JOHN PORTER WAS HEADED SOUTH BOUND ON HWY 662 IN AMELIA LA. WHEN HE MADE A LEFT TURN ON HWY 90 RAMP AND TURNED OVER THE TRACTOR TRAILER THAT HE WAS OPERATING ON THE TRUCKS PASSENGER SIDE COMING TO A REST ORIENTED SOUTH BOUND ON THE ENTRANCE RAMP.  MR. PORTER STATED THAT HE WAS TRAVELING AT 15 MPH AND IN SIXTH GEAR WHEN HE MADE HIS TURN ON THE ENTRACE RAMP WHEN THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS FLIPPED ON ITS SIDE.  TWO PEDESTRIANS (TBN) THAT WERE FOLLOWING MR. PORTER CALLED 911 AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 A.M.  MR PORTER STATED THAT HE SUFFERED A SPRAIN TO HIS LEFT KNEE WHEN THE TRACTOR TRAILER TURNED OVER. HE ALSO STATED THAT THE LACERATION TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF HIS FACE WAS INFLICTED AFTER THE INCIDENT AND WAS CAUSED BY BROKEN GLASS AS HE WAS TRYING TO EXIT THE CAB OF THE TRUCK.  MR PORTER WAS TRANSPORTED TO TECHE REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER AND WAS TREATED FOR A SPRAIN TO THE LEFT KNEE AND A LACERATION TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF HIS FACE THAT REQUIRED FIVE SUTURES. CHRIS SCALISI WAS NOTIFIED THAT THERE WAS AN INCIDENT INVOLVING A TRACTOR TRAILER AND EMPLOYEE MR. PORTER BY TALEN'S EMPLOYEE ROXY ROY.  MR. SCALISI THEN NOTIFIED STATE POLICE AT 8:14 WHICH WAS ALREADY ON THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT.  HE THEN NOTIFIED THE NRC, DEQ, COAST GUARD, AND OIL MOP.  OIL MOP ARRIVED ON THE INCIDENT SEEN APPROXIMATELY 9:20 A.M. AND IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE #2 DIESEL THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER'S TOP HATCH.  THE WRECKER SERVICE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 11:00 A.M. AND PRECEDED TO UPRIGHT THE TRACTOR TRAILER.  AT 12:00 P.M. UP-RIGHTING WAS COMPLETE AND TRANSFER OPERATIONS BEGAN BETWEEN THE DAMAGED TRAILER AND THE RECOVERING TRAILER.  TRANSFER OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED AT 1:30 P.M. APPROXIMATELY 2:45 THE DAMAGED TRACTOR TRAILER WAS TOWED OFF AND CLEAN UP STARTED. AT 3:07 OIL MOP FINISHED CLEAN UP AND DEMOBILIZED.  THERE WAS 40 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL THAT WAS SPILLED FROM THE INCIDENT.  MR. PORTER IS IN GOOD HEALTH AND HAS A FOLLOW UP APPOINTMENT IN ONE WEEK.  IT HAS BEEN RECOMMENDED TO THE CHIEF SAFETY OFFIER CHRIS SCALISI THAT MR. PORTER BE RETRAINED BEFORE RETURNING TO WORK SO THAT ANY FURTHER INCIDENTS MAY BE PREVENTED.  REPORTED PREPARED BY:  BRANDON GUNTER DATE OF REPORT:  9/27/08

column168: THIS "RELEASE" WAS THE RESULT OG A MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  A COPY OF THE POLICE REPORT "DESCRIPTION" IS ENCLOSED.  UPON LEARNING OF THE ACCIDENT/SPILL, WE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES OF INDIANAPOLIS, REPORTED THE SITUATION & THEY RESPONDED IN KIND & SENT A CREW TO THE SCENE.  THE OWNER OF OUR COMPANY WAS AT THE SCENE & HE AND I WERE COORDINATING THINGS VIA PHONE TO RESPOND TO THE SITUATION.
column169: DRIVER AWARENESS & ACCIDENT AVOIDANCE ARE 2 AREA CRITICAL TO ANY SITUATION.  WE HAVE DISCUSSED THIS ACCIDENT AT LENGTH WITH REGARD TO RECURRENCE.  A DRIVER HAS TO USE HIS OWN SENSES & ABILITIES, TO BE AWARE OF THEIR SURROUNDINGS; OBSERVATION & DRIVING SKILLS ARE THE TOOLS THEY HAVE AT THEIR DISPOSAL FOR ANY GIVEN SITUATION.  WE CONTINUALLY STRESS THESE THINGS.  THE MAIN THING BEYOND THE CONTROL OF ANY INDIVIDUAL COMPANY THAT I CAN THINK OF WOULD BE IF THE PUBLIC COULD SOMEHOW BE MADE MORE AWARE OF THE TRUCK DRIVERS & THE LEVEL OF DIFFICULTY THERE IS IN TRYING TO KEEP THE "TRANSPORTATION INDUSTRY" MOVING, SAFELY, ON A DAY TO DAY BASIS.

column168: ON FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 19, ASHLAND PICKED UP A TANK WAGON OF WASTE FLAMMABLE SOLVENTS (WASTE CODE: D001, PRIMARILY ISOPROPANOL) FROM A CUSTOMER, WITH THE INTENTION OF TRANSPORTING IT TO THE TSDF ON MONDAY.  HOWEVER, WHEN FACILITY PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SITE SUNDAY MORNING, THEY OBSERVED THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE HAD POPPED OPEN AND THAT THE TANK CONTENTS WERE VERY HOT.  A CHEMICAL REACTION HAD STARTED CAUSING THE WASTE TO BOIL.  SOME LIQUID MATERIAL SPRAYED OUT OF THE TANKER ONTO NEARBY EQUIPMENT WHEN THE RELIEF VALVE OPENED.  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS FROM THE CITY OF GARLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DALLAS HAZ-MAT TEAM CAME TO THE FACILITY TO REVIEW THE SITUATION.  THEY ORDERED A TEMPORARY EVACUATION OF THE ASHLAND FACILITY AND NEARBY BUILDINGS.  AFTER OBSERVING THE REACTION AND CONDITION OF THE TANKER, THEY DECIDED THAT THERE WAS NO LONGER A DANGER OF AN EXPLOSION AND ALLOWED EMPLOYEES TO RETURN TO THEIR RESPECTIVE BUILDINGS.  THE RESPONSE TEAMS RECOMMEND THAT THE MATERIAL BE ALLOWED TO COMPLETE ITS REACTION AND COOL PRIOR TO MOVING THE TANK WAGON.  ON OCTOBER 8, 2008, THE WASTE HAD FINALLY COMPLETED IT REACTION AND COOLED.  DUE TO THE POTENTIAL FOR DAMAGE TO THE TANK WAGON, THE WASTE WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK WAGON AND TAKEN FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN, ASHLAND HAS WORKED WITH THE CUSTOMER TO ENSURE WASTE STREAMS ARE NOT MIXED PRIOR TO PICK UP.  KEEPING THE WASTE STREAMS SEPARATED UNTIL THEY ARE RECEIVED AT THE DISPOSAL SITE WILL MINIMIZE THE RISK OF A CHEMICAL REACTION.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON I-49 NEAR ALEXANDRA, LA.  THE DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED BY AN UNSECURED ITEM IN THE CAB OF THE VEHICLE.  AS THE ITEM BEGAN TO FALL, THE DRIVER REACHED BEHIND HIM TO GRAB IT.  THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AT THIS TIME AND ROLLED THE VEHICLE ON ITS SIDE IN THE MEDAN.  PRODUCT FROM 5 TOTE TANKS BEGAN LEAKING AT THIS TIME.  A HOLE (APPROXIMATELY 10 X 4 INCHES) WAS FOUND AT THE BOTTOM CORNER TO ONE TOTE TANK.  THE OTHER TANKS APPARENTLY LEAKED FROM THE TOP LID.  THE CONTAMINATED SET WAS EXCAVATED AND DISPERSED OF THROUGH WASTE MANAGEMENT.  SOIL SAMPLES WERE OBTAINED TO VERIFY THAT THE SOIL WAS CLEANED TO LOUISIANA RECAP STANDARDS.
column169: STRESSED WITH ALL EMPLOYEEES THE NEED TO VERIFY THAT ALL ITEMS BOTH INSIDE & OUTSIDE OF THE CAB REMAIN SECURED.  HAVE SINCE IMPLEMENTED STRINGENT REQUIREMENTS ON COMPLETING REGULARLY SCHEDULED DEFENSE DRIVING PROGRAM.

column168: At approximatley 1000 on Tuesday the 30th of September, Passenger Roach checked his suitcase in for the trip to Miami.  The suitcase was tagged with his trips and sent down the belt for TSA screening. Upon screening, the TSA found liquids inside the bag and opened the bag up for physical search.  The physical search revealed six 12-ounce bottles of STP Gas Treatment and three bottles of STP Super Concentrated Fuel Injector Cleaner.  It appears that one of the bottles of fuel injector cleaner opened and spilled approximately six ounces which was absorbed by the passenger clothing inside the bag.  There was no release outside of the passenger's suitcase. The entire contents of the suitcase were bagged.  The entire contents as well as the suitcase will be disposed of as hazardous waste in accordance with regulations.
column169: Passenger failed to disclose hazardous materials in his suitcase.  Better education to the general public on what can and what cannot fly as well as ways for the passenger to give up his items when realized that he packed inappropriate items for transportation.

column168: DSR JOHN BUTLER HAD CRATE ON FORKLIFT AND WHILE DRIVING ON DOCK RAN OVER A BIG PIECE OF DUNNAGE / WOOD / AND CAUSED FORK LIFT TO JUMP TUMPING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TO LEAVE FORKS AND FALL ONTO GROUND CAUSING THE SPILL. AFTER THIS HAPPENED DSR CAME TO ME AND WE SECURED AREA AND CALLED CHEMTREC & JERRY PARRISH (SAFETY REP. FOR CONWAY) ABOUT SPILL. AFTER THIS WE CLEANED UP ACID WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED DAMAGED BATTERIES IN SALVAGE DRUM AND PUT IN OS&D HAZMAT BAY. CLEAN UP WAS NOT ALL DONE SO HAD TO CALL OUT FIRST RESPONSE TO SPRAY DOWN CRATE WITH BAKING SODA TO SOAK UP THE ACID TO MAKE IT NETRUALIZED FOR HANDLING AND REPACKED GOOD BATTERIES IN WOODEN CRATE.
column169: In future we have instructed all DSR's to make sure they store all extra dunnage / plywood / load bars / etc... up so we do not fumbly over them with fork lifts while hauling freight down dock. Also, make sure we are constantly watching where we are going on fork lift to avoid injury of any kind.
